-- 30-cell-spec-evolver.cell (R17, v0.2)
-- Tests: meta-level spec evolution via ‚äĘ‚ąė, ¬ß-quotation for code-as-data,
--        awkwardness detection, spec change proposals, rewrite & evaluation,
--        guard clauses for conditional dispatch, file-scope ‚ä®?,
--        ‚äĘ‚ąė-managed aspirational oracles, ‚äĘ= expression language validation
--
-- v0.2 changes from R16:
--   - Added file-scope ‚ä®? recovery policy (v0.2 blesses file-scope ‚ä®?)
--   - Guard clauses on compile-changes dispatch (is-clean = true / false)
--   - ‚äĘ‚ąė-managed cell oracles on identify-awkwardness are aspirational
--   - Awkward-program fragment rewritten with guard clauses (v0.2 showcase)
--   - ‚äĘ= expression language: all hard cells validated against v0.2 primitives
--   - given? on compile-changes for iterate-further‚Üíremaining (may be ‚ä•)
--   - Observations use ‚äĘ= expression language (v0.2 defined primitives)
--
-- Domain: Cell evolves its own specification. Writes a program that's awkward
-- in v0.1. Identifies WHY. Proposes spec change. Rewrites with change.
-- Evaluates: better? ‚äĘ‚ąė loop until no more awkwardness.
-- Output: proposed v0.2 spec changes.

‚ä®? on failure:
  retry with ¬ęoracle.failures¬Ľ appended to prompt
  max 3 attempts
‚ä®? on exhaustion:
  error-value(‚ä•)

‚äĘ spec-excerpt
  yield text

  ‚äĘ= text ‚Üź "## Cell v0.1 Spec ‚ÄĒ Key Constraints

Cells declare inputs with `given` and outputs with `yield`.
All inputs must be fully bound before evaluation.
There is no conditional `given` ‚ÄĒ every declared input is required.
There is no branching construct ‚ÄĒ cells execute linearly by data dependency.
There is no `try/fallback` pattern ‚ÄĒ oracle failure (‚ä®?) is the only recovery.
There is no way to express 'evaluate A, then choose B or C based on result.'
There is no guard clause on cells ‚ÄĒ a cell cannot say 'only run me if X.'
Versioning of evolved cells uses prime marks: cell, cell', cell''.

Open Questions from v0.1:
1. Error handling ‚ÄĒ what when ‚äĘ= throws or ‚ąī produces wrong type?
2. Versioning beyond prime marks ‚ÄĒ ¬ßcell''' doesn't scale.
3. Streaming ‚ÄĒ need ~ annotation for incremental input.
4. Oracle distinction ‚ÄĒ assert vs rule, soft vs hard preconditions."

‚äĘ awkward-program
  yield code, intent

  ‚äĘ= intent ‚Üź "A content moderation pipeline: classify text, then route to
different handlers based on classification. If toxic ‚Üí rewrite. If borderline ‚Üí
human-review. If clean ‚Üí pass through. This requires conditional dispatch
which Cell v0.1 has no syntax for."

  ‚äĘ= code ‚Üź "-- Awkward: conditional dispatch in Cell v0.1
-- We WANT: classify ‚Üí route to ONE of three handlers based on result.
-- We GET: all three handlers run, but two produce wasted work.

‚äĘ classify
  given text ‚Č° 'This product is terrible and whoever made it should feel bad.'
  yield label, confidence

  ‚ąī Classify ¬ętext¬Ľ as toxic, borderline, or clean.
     Output the label and your confidence (0-1).

  ‚ä® label ‚ąą {toxic, borderline, clean}
  ‚ä® confidence ‚ąą [0, 1]

‚äĘ handle-toxic
  given classify‚Üílabel where label = 'toxic'
  given classify‚Üíconfidence
  given text ‚Č° 'This product is terrible and whoever made it should feel bad.'
  yield rewritten

  ‚ąī Rewrite ¬ętext¬Ľ to remove toxicity while preserving the core feedback.

  ‚ä® rewritten is a non-toxic version of text

‚äĘ handle-borderline
  given classify‚Üílabel where label = 'borderline'
  given classify‚Üíconfidence
  yield action

  ‚ąī Flag for human review. Include ¬ęclassify‚Üíconfidence¬Ľ as context.

  ‚ä® action contains 'NEEDS_HUMAN_REVIEW'

‚äĘ handle-clean
  given classify‚Üílabel where label = 'clean'
  given text ‚Č° 'This product is terrible and whoever made it should feel bad.'
  yield output

  ‚ąī Pass ¬ętext¬Ľ through unchanged.

  ‚ä® output = text

‚äĘ merge-result
  given? handle-toxic‚Üírewritten
  given? handle-borderline‚Üíaction
  given? handle-clean‚Üíoutput
  given classify‚Üílabel
  yield final-output

  ‚ąī Select the result from whichever handler ran (non-‚ä• output).
     Exactly one of the three should be non-‚ä•.

  ‚ä® final-output ‚Č† ‚ä•"

‚äĘ identify-awkwardness
  given ¬ßawkward-program
  given awkward-program‚Üícode
  given awkward-program‚Üíintent
  given spec-excerpt‚Üítext
  yield problems[], root-causes[], awkwardness-score

  ‚ąī Analyze ¬ęawkward-program‚Üícode¬Ľ against the intent ¬ęawkward-program‚Üíintent¬Ľ.

    For each awkward pattern found, identify:
    1. WHAT is awkward (quote the code)
    2. WHY it's awkward (which spec constraint forces it)
    3. ROOT CAUSE in the spec (the missing construct or wrong assumption)
    4. SEVERITY: 1 (minor) to 5 (fundamental limitation)

    Categories to check:
    - WASTED COMPUTATION: Do cells run when they shouldn't?
    - BOILERPLATE: Do cells need manual 'if not my case' guards?
    - FRAGILITY: Does adding a 4th route require touching every cell?
    - READABILITY: Can a reader see the routing logic at a glance?
    - COMPOSABILITY: Can this pattern be reused without copy-paste?

    Set awkwardness-score = mean of severities.

  ‚ä® each problem has: quote, why, root-cause, severity
  ‚ä® each severity ‚ąą {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
  ‚ä® awkwardness-score = mean of all severities
  ‚ä® problems is non-empty (the program is intentionally awkward)

‚äĘ propose-spec-change
  given identify-awkwardness‚Üíproblems
  given identify-awkwardness‚Üíroot-causes
  given spec-excerpt‚Üítext
  yield proposed-syntax, rationale, compatibility-analysis

  ‚ąī For each root cause in ¬ęidentify-awkwardness‚Üíroot-causes¬Ľ, propose a
    concrete syntax addition or change to Cell v0.1 that would eliminate
    the awkwardness.

    Requirements for proposals:
    - Must be MINIMAL ‚ÄĒ smallest syntax change that fixes the problem
    - Must be COMPOSABLE ‚ÄĒ works with existing ‚äĘ, ‚ä®, ¬ß, ‚äĘ‚ąė mechanics
    - Must not break any existing valid Cell program
    - Must specify the new symbol/keyword and its semantics

    Consider these design options:
    - Guard clause: `given x where condition` (cell only evaluates if true)
    - Pattern match: `‚äĘ handle | classify‚Üílabel = "toxic"` (variant cells)
    - Dispatch cell: `‚äĘ‚äł route(classify‚Üílabel) { toxic: ..., clean: ... }`
    - Conditional given: `given? x if condition` (optional dependency)
    - Bottom propagation: skipped cells yield ‚ä•, downstream uses given?

    Output the proposed syntax, rationale for choosing it, and analysis
    of backward compatibility with v0.1.

  ‚ä® proposed-syntax defines at least one new construct
  ‚ä® rationale addresses every root cause
  ‚ä® compatibility-analysis confirms no breakage of existing programs

‚äĘ rewrite-program
  given ¬ßawkward-program
  given awkward-program‚Üícode
  given awkward-program‚Üíintent
  given propose-spec-change‚Üíproposed-syntax
  yield code', awkward-parts-remaining[]

  ‚ąī Rewrite ¬ęawkward-program‚Üícode¬Ľ using the proposed syntax from
    ¬ępropose-spec-change‚Üíproposed-syntax¬Ľ.

    The rewritten program must:
    - Achieve the same intent as ¬ęawkward-program‚Üíintent¬Ľ
    - Use the proposed syntax wherever it eliminates awkwardness
    - NOT introduce new awkwardness
    - Be shorter or equal in length to the original

    List any remaining awkward parts that the proposed syntax didn't fix.

  ‚ä® code' achieves the same intent as awkward-program‚Üíintent
  ‚ä® code' uses at least one construct from proposed-syntax
  ‚ä® code' does not contain 'N/A' hack patterns

‚äĘ evaluate-improvement
  given awkward-program‚Üícode
  given rewrite-program‚Üícode'
  given rewrite-program‚Üíawkward-parts-remaining
  given identify-awkwardness‚Üíawkwardness-score
  yield new-score, improvement-delta, is-clean, verdict

  ‚ąī Compare the original code ¬ęawkward-program‚Üícode¬Ľ with the rewrite
    ¬ęrewrite-program‚Üícode'¬Ľ.

    Score the rewrite on the same 5 categories (wasted computation,
    boilerplate, fragility, readability, composability). Each 1-5.
    Calculate new-score as the mean.
    improvement-delta = original awkwardness-score ‚ąí new-score.
    is-clean = true if new-score ‚Č§ 1.5 AND no remaining awkward parts
    have severity ‚Č• 4.

    Verdict: summarize whether the spec change is worth adopting.

  ‚ä® new-score ‚Č§ identify-awkwardness‚Üíawkwardness-score
  ‚ä® improvement-delta ‚Č• 0
  ‚ä® if new-score ‚Č§ 1.5 and awkward-parts-remaining all have severity < 4 then is-clean = true
  ‚ä® if new-score > 1.5 then is-clean = false

‚äĘ‚ąė evolve-spec(awkward-program)
  through identify-awkwardness, propose-spec-change, rewrite-program, evaluate-improvement
  until evaluate-improvement‚Üíis-clean = true
  max 3

‚äĘ compile-changes
  given propose-spec-change‚Üíproposed-syntax
  given propose-spec-change‚Üírationale
  given propose-spec-change‚Üícompatibility-analysis
  given evaluate-improvement‚Üíverdict
  given evaluate-improvement‚Üíis-clean where is-clean = true
  given rewrite-program‚Üícode'
  yield v02-changes

  ‚ąī Compile the proposed v0.2 spec changes into a structured document:

    ## Proposed Cell v0.2 Changes

    For each accepted syntax change:
    - Symbol/keyword and its meaning
    - Formal syntax (BNF-like)
    - Semantics (how eval-one handles it)
    - Example (before/after)
    - Backward compatibility note

  ‚ä® v02-changes includes at least one concrete syntax proposal
  ‚ä® v02-changes includes before/after examples
  ‚ä® v02-changes includes backward compatibility analysis

‚äĘ iterate-further
  given propose-spec-change‚Üíproposed-syntax
  given evaluate-improvement‚Üíverdict
  given evaluate-improvement‚Üíis-clean where is-clean = false
  given rewrite-program‚Üíawkward-parts-remaining
  yield remaining[], next-focus

  ‚ąī The rewrite is not clean yet. List the remaining awkwardnesses from
    ¬ęrewrite-program‚Üíawkward-parts-remaining¬Ľ that the proposed syntax
    didn't fix, and identify which one to focus on next.

  ‚ä® len(remaining) > 0
  ‚ä® next-focus names a specific remaining awkwardness

-- Observations

‚äĘ= obs-1 ‚Üź "The ‚äĘ‚ąė loop here evolves the PROGRAM, not the spec. Each iteration
  rewrites awkward-program‚Üícode with progressively better spec proposals. The
  spec changes accumulate in compile-changes, which reads the final iteration's
  proposals. Under v0.2, the oracles on identify-awkwardness are aspirational ‚ÄĒ
  the ‚äĘ‚ąė loop's `until` condition (is-clean = true) is the true convergence gate."

‚äĘ= obs-2 ‚Üź "The awkward-program fragment has been rewritten with v0.2 guard
  clauses and given?/‚ä• propagation. The R16 version used the N/A hack (all
  branches run, irrelevant ones output 'N/A'). The R17 version uses
  `given classify‚Üílabel where label = 'toxic'` so only the relevant handler
  executes. Skipped handlers yield ‚ä•. merge-result uses given? to accept ‚ä•
  and select the non-‚ä• result. This IS the spec change the program discovers."

‚äĘ= obs-3 ‚Üź "Self-referential irony: program 30 was the motivating example for
  guard clauses in the v0.2 spec. The R17 version embeds the v0.2 solution
  (guard clauses) inside its own awkward-program fragment, then re-discovers
  why it works. The evolver validates the spec change it already contains."

‚äĘ= obs-4 ‚Üź "Guard-gated dispatch on compile-changes vs iterate-further replaces
  the R16 pattern where a single compile-changes cell handled both clean and
  not-clean cases. Under v0.2, `given ... where is-clean = true` sends the
  program to compile-changes; `given ... where is-clean = false` sends it to
  iterate-further. Exactly one fires. No wasted evaluation."

‚äĘ= obs-5 ‚Üź "The ‚äĘ= expression language validation is subtle here: obs cells
  use string literals (valid), evaluate-improvement uses arithmetic comparison
  (new-score ‚Č§ 1.5, valid), and guard clauses use equality checks (is-clean =
  true, valid). All conform to v0.2 defined primitives. No false crystallization."
